1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:04,840
 Hello, and welcome to our lecture on dynamic web content.

2
00:00:04,840 --> 00:00:07,200
 It may seem kind of weird to be talking about building web

3
00:00:07,200 --> 00:00:09,680
 applications, and to when we start out

4
00:00:09,680 --> 00:00:11,840
 talking about building web applications,

5
00:00:11,840 --> 00:00:14,320
 that we're going to talk about protocols and stuff.

6
00:00:14,320 --> 00:00:18,360
 But in a way, when you are building a web application,

7
00:00:18,360 --> 00:00:19,980
 if you don't understand the protocol,

8
00:00:19,980 --> 00:00:21,240
 and you just sort of say, I changed

9
00:00:21,240 --> 00:00:23,120
 this little bit of code, and I hit refresh,

10
00:00:23,120 --> 00:00:26,080
 and some magic happened, you really

11
00:00:26,080 --> 00:00:29,520
 are cheating yourself in terms of becoming

12
00:00:29,520 --> 00:00:31,800
 a really good web application developer.

13
00:00:31,800 --> 00:00:33,480
 Because ultimately, these protocols

14
00:00:33,480 --> 00:00:35,240
 are what enable web applications.

15
00:00:35,240 --> 00:00:39,080
 And as you go forward and use frameworks,

16
00:00:39,080 --> 00:00:42,040
 you don't need to know all these things in detail.

17
00:00:42,040 --> 00:00:45,040
 But when you debug your applications, you absolutely do.

18
00:00:45,040 --> 00:00:49,600
 And I don't know if you've had your Firefox console,

19
00:00:49,600 --> 00:00:51,640
 or looked at things, and watched.

20
00:00:51,640 --> 00:00:53,880
 There's so much complexity going on.

21
00:00:53,880 --> 00:00:57,200
 And when you're using a web application,

22
00:00:57,200 --> 00:01:00,360
 hopefully everything works, and that complexity is hidden from you.

23
00:01:00,360 --> 00:01:03,360
 So if you have some interest in this,

24
00:01:03,360 --> 00:01:05,760
 and want to go even lower to sort of more of the network

25
00:01:05,760 --> 00:01:09,720
 protocols, not just the HTTP protocols,

26
00:01:09,720 --> 00:01:12,920
 I've written a free book on networking called Introduction

27
00:01:12,920 --> 00:01:16,560
 to Networking, How the Internet Works, that you are welcome.

28
00:01:16,560 --> 00:01:19,400
 You can buy a print if you want, but it's also completely free,

29
00:01:19,400 --> 00:01:22,840
 like every book that I write these days.

30
00:01:22,840 --> 00:01:25,440
 And so if we take a look at what we're

31
00:01:25,440 --> 00:01:27,840
 going to really be talking about in this lecture

32
00:01:27,840 --> 00:01:30,560
 and in this web application course,

33
00:01:30,560 --> 00:01:33,680
 is the technologies, the different technologies

34
00:01:33,680 --> 00:01:36,560
 that are used to, in effect, produce a web page, right?

35
00:01:36,560 --> 00:01:38,480
 So we have a web page over here.

36
00:01:38,480 --> 00:01:40,840
 You go to URL, dub, dub, dub, data--

37
00:01:40,840 --> 00:01:45,360
 I mean, data.pr4e.org/page1.htm.

38
00:01:45,360 --> 00:01:47,760
 And here comes a page.

39
00:01:47,760 --> 00:01:50,280
 And this is like a super simple page.

40
00:01:50,280 --> 00:01:52,080
 But there are so many technologies,

41
00:01:52,080 --> 00:01:55,880
 like how browsers work with JavaScript, and jQuery, and CSS,

42
00:01:55,880 --> 00:01:58,840
 and eventually Vue, and things like that.

43
00:01:58,840 --> 00:02:01,000
 That's a whole set of front-end technologies.

44
00:02:01,000 --> 00:02:03,360
 And then there's sort of back-end technologies,

45
00:02:03,360 --> 00:02:05,800
 like Django, or Flask, and databases.

46
00:02:05,800 --> 00:02:08,120
 And we're going to learn--

47
00:02:08,120 --> 00:02:10,080
 my focus in this class is less about how

48
00:02:10,080 --> 00:02:13,040
 to make it all look beautiful, although that's important,

49
00:02:13,040 --> 00:02:17,160
 and more about how to deal with the back-end.

50
00:02:17,160 --> 00:02:19,480
 So what we're going to see is these technologies that

51
00:02:19,480 --> 00:02:22,440
 define the look and feel and the interactivity of your web

52
00:02:22,440 --> 00:02:27,520
 pages, but also then how data and HTML, CSS, and JavaScript

53
00:02:27,520 --> 00:02:29,800
 are served up by the remote server.

54
00:02:29,800 --> 00:02:31,840
 And so the internet here is in the middle.

55
00:02:31,840 --> 00:02:34,960
 The browser is sitting on your laptop, or your phone,

56
00:02:34,960 --> 00:02:37,160
 or whatever, and it has all these technologies built

57
00:02:37,160 --> 00:02:37,880
 into it.

58
00:02:37,880 --> 00:02:39,000
 It makes requests.

59
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:44,000
 And then the server comes back with responses.

60
00:02:44,000 --> 00:02:47,920
 And so the simplest version of this protocol

61
00:02:47,920 --> 00:02:50,840
 is that you click on a tag, and when you click on that tag,

62
00:02:50,840 --> 00:02:53,720
 you get a new web page.

63
00:02:53,720 --> 00:02:55,880
 Now, if you watch your debug console,

64
00:02:55,880 --> 00:02:59,360
 you will see that sometimes it's 120 different request response

65
00:02:59,360 --> 00:03:01,840
 cycles used to construct the page.

66
00:03:01,840 --> 00:03:04,040
 But in a sense, they're all the same.

67
00:03:04,040 --> 00:03:06,360
 Now, as we move to things like HTTP/2,

68
00:03:06,360 --> 00:03:08,880
 there are ways to pull down multiple documents

69
00:03:08,880 --> 00:03:10,400
 in a single connection, but we'll

70
00:03:10,400 --> 00:03:13,960
 stick with the old HTTP/1 way of thinking about it.

71
00:03:13,960 --> 00:03:16,300
 In the simplest form, the browser

72
00:03:16,300 --> 00:03:18,760
 asks for a document, and then retrieves the document,

73
00:03:18,760 --> 00:03:19,960
 and then shows the document.

74
00:03:19,960 --> 00:03:23,840
 And that is the basic request response cycle.

75
00:03:23,840 --> 00:03:26,040
 So if you look at how this works,

76
00:03:26,040 --> 00:03:28,320
 that browser is an application running

77
00:03:28,320 --> 00:03:31,440
 inside your computer on your laptop, or your phone.

78
00:03:31,440 --> 00:03:32,960
 That is a piece of code.

79
00:03:32,960 --> 00:03:35,560
 And in that, it's got a connection

80
00:03:35,560 --> 00:03:38,640
 to the screen, or the keyboard, or the mouse, or whatever.

81
00:03:38,640 --> 00:03:41,640
 And it's watching for events, meaning

82
00:03:41,640 --> 00:03:44,680
 that you're going to go, and you're going to click somewhere.

83
00:03:44,680 --> 00:03:46,440
 And then this application is going

84
00:03:46,440 --> 00:03:47,940
 to respond to the events.

85
00:03:47,940 --> 00:03:49,600
 So on a web page, in the simplest case,

86
00:03:49,600 --> 00:03:51,200
 you've got stuff that you can click on,

87
00:03:51,200 --> 00:03:52,720
 and stuff that you can't.

88
00:03:52,720 --> 00:03:55,160
 And you go find your way through whatever

89
00:03:55,160 --> 00:03:57,120
 to click on part of that web page.

90
00:03:57,120 --> 00:04:00,400
 And that click is intercepted by the application,

91
00:04:00,400 --> 00:04:04,120
 whether it's Chrome, or Firefox, or Safari, running

92
00:04:04,120 --> 00:04:06,960
 on your piece of equipment.

93
00:04:06,960 --> 00:04:09,680
 And then that application then opens

94
00:04:09,680 --> 00:04:13,880
 what's called a network socket, a socket across the network

95
00:04:13,880 --> 00:04:17,880
 to a web server, and sends a request.

96
00:04:17,880 --> 00:04:19,640
 And that request, as we'll see in a bit,

97
00:04:19,640 --> 00:04:21,960
 is a specially formatted request.

98
00:04:21,960 --> 00:04:24,200
 It has a get command, and then it

99
00:04:24,200 --> 00:04:27,040
 has the URL that it wants to get from the web server.

100
00:04:27,040 --> 00:04:31,000
 And then the web server does a bunch of work inside itself,

101
00:04:31,000 --> 00:04:34,040
 a bunch of work inside itself, maybe reading disk files,

102
00:04:34,040 --> 00:04:36,360
 and running the programs, generating

103
00:04:36,360 --> 00:04:38,040
 what it is that you want.

104
00:04:38,040 --> 00:04:40,160
 And then it sends the response back

105
00:04:40,160 --> 00:04:41,940
 on that same socket connection.

106
00:04:41,940 --> 00:04:44,880
 So there's like this socket connection through which

107
00:04:44,880 --> 00:04:47,080
 all of this stuff is viewed.

108
00:04:47,080 --> 00:04:51,420
 And so the HTML is kind of the basic thing that comes back.

109
00:04:51,420 --> 00:04:53,520
 As we go further, we'll see that it's not just

110
00:04:53,520 --> 00:04:57,200
 HTML that comes back, but other things as well that come back.

111
00:04:57,200 --> 00:05:01,200
 And so when the browser receives that HTML, then it says,

112
00:05:01,200 --> 00:05:02,840
 oh, I know what HTML is.

113
00:05:02,840 --> 00:05:05,560
 I've got this header one tag.

114
00:05:05,560 --> 00:05:07,640
 Here, let me change the color of this thing

115
00:05:07,640 --> 00:05:11,400
 so you can see it a little better.

116
00:05:11,400 --> 00:05:12,840
 Yellow is way better.

117
00:05:12,840 --> 00:05:17,280
 OK, so when the browser receives this page,

118
00:05:17,280 --> 00:05:20,000
 it sort of sees it, and it looks at it.

119
00:05:20,000 --> 00:05:21,800
 And then it looks at all the HTML.

120
00:05:21,800 --> 00:05:25,960
 And so part of this course is to understand the syntax of HTML.

121
00:05:25,960 --> 00:05:30,080
 That itself is how to build good HTML and CSS

122
00:05:30,080 --> 00:05:31,560
 and how to make it look beautiful.

123
00:05:31,560 --> 00:05:34,240
 But ultimately, something in that HTML, plus its CSS,

124
00:05:34,240 --> 00:05:37,680
 plus its JavaScript, leads to a visual display of the page.

125
00:05:37,680 --> 00:05:39,760
 And then that's the thing you see.

126
00:05:39,760 --> 00:05:45,240
 And so this is the request-response cycle.

127
00:05:45,240 --> 00:05:48,240
 So up next, we're going to talk about what these network

128
00:05:48,240 --> 00:05:51,740
 sockets are or the things that fundamentally underlie

129
00:05:51,740 --> 00:05:54,280
 this request-response cycle.

